# CareClarity — Comprehensive Tech Stack & Implementation Methodology

> **CareClarity** is an AI-powered healthcare platform designed to assist parents and caregivers of children with Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) and related neurodevelopmental conditions. It connects families to verified specialists, provides AI-driven guidance, and offers curated resources — all within a safe, accessible, and modern web & mobile experience.

---

## 1. Core Technologies & Languages

| Technology | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **Python** | Backend API, Server Logic & AI Integration |
| **JavaScript** | Frontend web development & Mobile application logic |

---

## 2. Application Frameworks

| Framework | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **React** | Web frontend framework for building dynamic, single-page UI components |
| **React Native** | Cross-platform mobile application development (iOS & Android) |
| **Django / Flask** | Backend frameworks for managing RESTful APIs, routing, and server-side business logic |

---

## 3. Database Architecture

| Database | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **PostgreSQL** | Relational database handling structured User Data (profiles, appointments, application state) |
| **MongoDB** | NoSQL database for unstructured/semi-structured Resources, articles, and dynamic content |

---

## 4. Artificial Intelligence & Machine Learning

| Technology | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **TensorFlow / PyTorch** | Core AI frameworks used to build, train, and deploy models |
| **Generative Assessment** | Custom models to assess inputs, identify patterns, and generate "Risk Flags" for caregivers based on child data |
| **Recommendation Engine** | ML system to intelligently match children and parents with relevant specialists and curated resources |

---

## 5. Cloud Infrastructure & DevOps

| Service | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **AWS (Amazon Web Services)** | Primary cloud provider hosting the entire application architecture |
| **AWS S3** | Object storage for user uploads, profile photos, and static assets |
| **AWS RDS** | Managed relational database service for scaling PostgreSQL |
| **Docker** | Containerization of microservices ensuring consistent environments across dev and production |
| **Kubernetes** | Container orchestration for scaling, managing, and updating the microservices fleet automatically |

---

## 6. Implementation Methodology

### 6.1. Microservices Architecture
The platform is built on a scalable microservices architecture divided into three primary layers:
1. **Presentation Layer:** React (Web) and React Native (Mobile) rendering dynamic interfaces and handling user interactions.
2. **Service Layer:** Python-based APIs (Django/Flask) handling business logic, the recommendation matching engine, and AI assessments.
3. **Data Layer:** PostgreSQL (User Data) and MongoDB (Resources) providing robust and distinct persistence strategies.

### 6.2. Application Process Flow
1. **Parent Inputs Data:** Caregivers complete questionnaires and input specific challenges, behavioral patterns, and goals via the UI.
2. **AI Assessment:** The Python-based backend securely passes this data to the TensorFlow/PyTorch NLP models.
3. **Risk Flags Generated:** The AI Engine processes the inputs to identify "Risk Flags" (e.g., developmental delays, sensory sensitivities).
4. **Recommendation Engine:** Based on the generated flags, the matching engine suggests appropriate, verified specialists and highly relevant learning resources.

### 6.3. Data Security & Cloud Storage
- **Secure Handling:** Strict role-based access controls and encrypted data transmission.
- **Cloud-Based Identity:** Secure storage of all clinical reports, assessments, and sensitive user data strictly housed within AWS secure enclaves meeting modern compliance standards.

### 6.4. Phased Development Cycle
1. **UI Phase:** Designing and implementing the Presentation Layer across web (React) and mobile (React Native).
2. **AI Model Phase:** Aggregating data sets, training the AI algorithms, and validating the output of Risk Flags via Django/Flask/PyTorch.
3. **Matching Engine Phase:** Developing the logic mapping specific generated flags to the database (MongoDB) of resources and specialists.
4. **Deployment Phase:** Containerizing applications via Docker, deploying to AWS, and managing infrastructure via Kubernetes.
